arch:property.oc:show_val: This locus is a clearly-defined rectilinear vertical channel created at the juncture of the Semi-circular Feature (Locus 10) wall and the resumption of the west section of the Wall Locus 6 by the positioning of the wall ashlars. It extends from the level of the Suspended Floor (Locus 13) down to the Locus 17 terracotta tile floor. It appears to have served as a flue bay. No ceramic canalization tiles were found in situ, but a substantial number of such fragments were found in proximity in the Locus 12 fill. The top opening of the flue was blocked by a limestone capital volute when discovered; this architectural fragment, thought at the time to be a re-used element in the suspended floor, is catalogued under as coming from Locus 13 (Seq. No. 126837). It can not be determined if the emplacement of this capital fragment was intentional or accidental.
0.30 m north south-by-0.25 m east west.
Subflooring, North of Vault Locus 18, interior West face of Locus 10.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre-CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. At this time the northwest subterranean channel is damaged and clogged with CE 1st c. pottery. Repairs are made to the Hexagonal Pavement as well as to the East Exedra walls. Bath Complex built.
Canalization Flue to North Side of Vault Locus 18
